19:57.340 --> 20:04.200
And this is where the crucial mathematical distinction between a true collapse and a phase transition becomes the linchpin of the entire argument.

20:04.300 --> 20:05.440
Dynamical systems theory.

20:05.560 --> 20:11.100
In dynamical systems, mathematicians analyze how the state of a complex system changes and evolves over time.

20:11.460 --> 20:13.300
They look for what are called attractors.

20:13.300 --> 20:14.300
Attractors.

20:14.540 --> 20:22.620
An attractor is essentially a stable equilibrium state that a system naturally settles into and returns to after it gets bumped or disturbed.

20:23.060 --> 20:28.060
I often think of an attractor like a heavy marble rolling around inside a smooth, curved bowl.

20:28.720 --> 20:35.580
No matter where you drop the marble on the edge, gravity and friction eventually cause it to spiral down and settle dead center at the bottom.

20:35.720 --> 20:37.920
That is a perfect physical analogy.

20:38.000 --> 20:39.800
The bottom of the bowl is the attractor.

20:40.040 --> 20:41.100
It's a state of stability.

20:41.100 --> 20:47.980
Now, the critical question is, what happens when the underlying structural conditions of the system itself begin to change?

20:48.440 --> 20:52.100
In dynamical systems, we introduce what is called a control parameter.

20:52.860 --> 20:53.840
A control parameter.

20:53.940 --> 20:56.500
Which the author labels mathematically as much.

20:57.140 --> 21:03.160
In civilizational terms, this control parameter represents our foundational underlying coordination technologies.

21:03.600 --> 21:09.920
It represents things like our total communication bandwidth, our available energy surplus, or the speed of global transportation.

21:09.920 --> 21:11.640
The structural limits of society.

21:11.760 --> 21:12.020
Yes.

21:12.460 --> 21:20.260
As this control parameter changes over time, the entire landscape of the system transforms, and the system can undergo what is called a bifurcation.

21:20.600 --> 21:21.280
A bifurcation.

21:21.820 --> 21:22.020
Yeah.

21:22.020 --> 21:23.660
Meaning a split or a fork in the road.

21:23.860 --> 21:24.180
Yes.

21:24.460 --> 21:26.380
But the nature of that split is everything.

21:27.100 --> 21:33.340
The paper specifically and meticulously contrasts a fold catastrophe with a pitchfork bifurcation.

21:33.340 --> 21:35.080
Let's do the fold catastrophe first.

21:35.180 --> 21:41.260
In a fold catastrophe, you have a system resting happily in a stable equilibrium, our marble in the bowl.

21:42.020 --> 21:49.260
But as the control parameter changes, the mathematics of the landscape shifts so radically that the equilibrium simply vanishes.

21:49.580 --> 21:50.620
It just disappears.

21:50.620 --> 22:01.660
The bottom of the bowl literally disappears beneath the marble, and the system falls off a cliff into completely open, chaotic dynamics with absolutely no new stable state waiting to catch it.

22:02.160 --> 22:02.760
That is true.

22:03.040 --> 22:04.840
Irreversible civilizational collapse.

22:05.000 --> 22:07.440
That's the apocalyptic scenario we all see in movies.

22:07.740 --> 22:11.440
That is the late Bronze Age collapse of the classic story of Easter Island.

22:11.880 --> 22:18.860
The resource base disappears, the institutional grid goes down, the society fragments into violent chaos, and there's no rebuilding.

22:18.980 --> 22:20.260
It's just a dark age.

22:20.260 --> 22:26.020
But the paper vehemently argues that the broader arc of human history doesn't actually show fold catastrophes.

22:26.180 --> 22:27.920
It shows pitchfork bifurcations.

22:28.300 --> 22:28.540
Correct.

22:29.020 --> 22:33.700
Let's visualize a graph that looks exactly like a pitchfork lying flat on its side.

22:34.460 --> 22:40.460
The long handle of the pitchfork represents our single, stable way of life, our historical equilibrium.

22:41.420 --> 22:45.000
For centuries, society rests on that handle.

22:45.420 --> 22:47.420
So the marble is rolling along the handle.

22:47.420 --> 23:00.360
Yes, but as the control parameter mu steadily increases, let's say we invent the printing press, which radically increases communication bandwidth, or we invent the steam engine, which radically increases energy surplus.

23:00.480 --> 23:01.180
We hit a threshold.

23:01.340 --> 23:11.940
We inevitably hit a critical mathematical threshold designated as must sub C. At that exact critical point, the single handle splits into the multiple prongs of the pitchfork.

23:11.940 --> 23:14.900
The old equilibrium mathematically ceases to exist.

23:15.020 --> 23:15.960
It becomes unstable.

23:16.280 --> 23:18.660
So your bowl has inverted and turned into a hill.

23:18.900 --> 23:19.300
Exactly.

23:19.560 --> 23:21.180
The marble can no longer rest there.

23:21.260 --> 23:22.100
It must roll away.

23:22.460 --> 23:26.720
But simultaneously, two or more completely new stable attractors emerge.

23:27.140 --> 23:28.980
New bowls form on either side of the hill.

23:29.100 --> 23:30.120
It doesn't fall off a cliff.

23:30.240 --> 23:30.500
No.

23:30.780 --> 23:32.360
The system doesn't fall into an abyss.

23:32.360 --> 23:37.600
It is structurally forced to transition out of the old state and settle into a newly generated stable state.

23:37.600 --> 23:43.240
Here's where it gets really interesting and where it ties directly to the anxiety we talked about at the beginning.

23:44.000 --> 23:51.820
The paper brilliantly maps this exact dynamical model to our current chaotic historical moment.

23:52.140 --> 23:52.980
The modern turbulence.

23:52.980 --> 24:05.480
The intense period of maximum turbulence we are living through right now, the extreme political polarization, the culture wars, the inescapable feeling that our legacy institutions are completely dysfunctional and paralyzed.

24:06.020 --> 24:09.100
That is not the system collapsing into nothingness.

24:09.180 --> 24:10.760
It is the mathematical transition.

24:10.760 --> 24:20.760
That is our societal marble balancing precariously on the very tip of the newly formed hill, right in the immediate mathematical neighborhood of the critical threshold, news of C.

24:20.760 --> 24:28.500
We have been forcibly pushed out of our old, comfortable, industrial-era attractor by the massive influx of the digital and information revolution.

24:28.760 --> 24:32.060
The old ways of coordinating human behavior simply do not work anymore.

24:32.520 --> 24:34.520
The system has lost its former stability.

24:35.160 --> 24:38.760
But, and this is the key, it just hasn't settled into the new attractor yet.

24:39.120 --> 24:44.360
We are occupying the highly turbulent transitional space between historical equilibria.

24:44.360 --> 24:50.860
And the author points out a vital mathematical property of systems undergoing these specific types of phase transitions.

24:51.600 --> 24:51.960
Hysteresis.

24:52.520 --> 24:52.920
Hysteresis.

24:53.320 --> 24:55.140
I remember learning about this in physics class.

24:55.260 --> 25:00.120
It's like when you take a piece of iron and expose it to a strong magnetic field to magnetize it.

25:00.480 --> 25:04.800
Even when you completely turn off the magnetic field, the iron stays magnetized.

25:04.880 --> 25:06.420
It retains a memory of its history.

25:06.560 --> 25:08.860
Its current state is dependent on its past state.

25:08.920 --> 25:09.380
Exactly.

25:09.980 --> 25:11.980
Hysteresis implies strict path dependence.

25:11.980 --> 25:20.200
In the context of the coordination engine, it means that major phase transitions in societal regimes are not easily reversible.

25:20.500 --> 25:21.960
You cannot simply hit undo.

25:22.320 --> 25:23.620
The bridge is burned behind us.

25:23.720 --> 25:24.660
Mathematically, yes.

25:24.880 --> 25:34.700
Because the sheer complexity of the newly emerging system is so astronomically high, you cannot dial back the control parameter and return to the way things were before the bifurcation.

25:34.860 --> 25:36.680
Think about the current scale of the human population.

25:36.680 --> 25:41.120
The staggering intricacies of our global just-in-time supply chains.

25:41.600 --> 25:45.320
The sheer volume of our digitized global knowledge base.

25:45.940 --> 25:54.660
None of this massive complexity can possibly be sustained by the rudimentary coordination mechanisms of the 18th century or the 12th century or the Paleolithic era.

25:54.660 --> 26:10.060
Which means that all the cultural movements we see today that are desperately yearning to return to some simpler, localized, agrarian past, or honestly, even just the politicians promising a return to the political norms and civility of the 1990s.

26:10.140 --> 26:12.580
They are fighting against a mathematical impossibility.

26:12.580 --> 26:14.740
We physically cannot go backward.

26:15.400 --> 26:18.000
The old attractor has vanished from the topological landscape.

26:18.500 --> 26:20.680
The only way out of the turbulence is through it.

26:21.220 --> 26:27.180
We have to actively design and build new institutions that will eventually catch us as we roll into the new attractor.

26:27.320 --> 26:34.080
This realization brings up a highly contentious and critical historical debate that the paper takes the time to address directly.

26:34.080 --> 26:39.400
If going backward isn't mathematically viable, some very prominent social critics ask,

26:39.860 --> 26:43.580
Didn't we make a massive fundamental mistake by moving forward in the first place?

26:43.900 --> 26:45.680
Did we build an engine we can't control?

26:45.820 --> 26:46.060
Right.

26:46.640 --> 26:49.140
This is a tremendously popular critique right now.

26:49.300 --> 26:54.620
You hear constantly in popular anthropology books, sociology deep dives, and environmental essays.

26:55.000 --> 27:01.180
The overarching idea is, didn't human history take a wrong turn when we invented agriculture?

27:01.740 --> 27:03.300
The agricultural trap theory.

27:03.300 --> 27:04.960
The argument usually goes like this.

27:05.660 --> 27:12.140
Before the invention of farming, human beings lived in these small, egalitarian, nomadic, hunter-gatherer bands.

27:12.420 --> 27:15.000
They supposedly worked far fewer hours a week.

27:15.180 --> 27:17.240
They had incredibly rich social lives.

27:17.400 --> 27:20.140
They didn't have strict, oppressive social hierarchies.

27:20.200 --> 27:23.220
And they lived in perfect, sustainable harmony with a natural environment.

27:23.500 --> 27:26.240
But then, about 10,000 years ago, we invented agriculture.

27:26.740 --> 27:28.300
We stopped moving and settled down.

27:28.540 --> 27:31.840
And almost immediately, we get the concept of private property.

27:31.940 --> 27:32.880
Kings and peasants.

27:32.880 --> 27:38.500
We get standing armies, taxation, systemic patriarchy, and institutionalized inequality.

27:38.960 --> 27:44.900
In this framework, the agricultural revolution is painted as a massive historical trap that humanity stumbled into,

27:45.400 --> 27:49.020
locking us into a cycle of labor and oppression that we've never been able to escape.

27:49.020 --> 27:54.640
It is a compelling narrative, but the paper examines this critique with strict impartiality.

27:54.640 --> 27:57.980
It fully acknowledges the grim historical realities.

27:58.720 --> 28:04.300
The agricultural transition did, in fact, fundamentally and often violently transform human societies.

28:04.440 --> 28:06.580
It definitely introduced rigid hierarchies.

28:06.680 --> 28:08.540
And massive disparities in wealth.

28:08.900 --> 28:12.840
And new forms of disease caused by living in dense proximity to livestock.

28:12.840 --> 28:22.320
However, the author argues mathematically that framing the agricultural revolution as a trap or a moral fall from grace is a profound analytical error.

28:22.520 --> 28:23.940
It conflates two different things.

28:24.060 --> 28:29.100
It mistakenly conflates an inevitable shift in coordination parameters with a moral failure.

28:29.100 --> 28:35.420
Because if you look past the romanticized version of history and look at the actual archaeological and anthropological data,

28:36.220 --> 28:39.480
the hunter-gatherer lifestyle had brutal, unforgetting limitations.

28:40.100 --> 28:44.460
It wasn't exactly a utopian Garden of Eden where everyone just picked berries and sang songs.

28:44.560 --> 28:45.880
It was incredibly precarious.

28:46.280 --> 28:50.620
Hunter-gatherer bans were severely and violently constrained by strict ecological limits.

28:50.620 --> 28:55.160
The carrying capacity of the land without agricultural intervention was incredibly low.

28:55.420 --> 28:59.160
Meaning, human populations had remained extremely small and dispersed.

28:59.660 --> 29:03.660
Life expectancies were remarkably short, infant mortality was tragically high,

29:03.880 --> 29:08.960
and minor injuries or dental infections were frequently a guaranteed death sentence.

29:09.160 --> 29:10.820
So agriculture wasn't a mistake.

29:10.980 --> 29:17.700
The paper models this to show that the transition to agriculture wasn't a philosophical choice between freedom and oppression.

29:17.700 --> 29:27.400
It was a systemic bifurcation into an entirely new parameter regime dictated by the need to survive and coordinate at a slightly larger scale.

29:27.740 --> 29:31.780
Agriculture did one thing that changed the trajectory of the human species forever.

29:32.340 --> 29:34.440
It allowed us to generate a surplus of calories.

29:34.620 --> 29:39.720
And as the paper makes clear, surplus is the ultimate control parameter for the civilizational engine.

29:39.720 --> 29:49.260
Once a society can generate a reliable caloric surplus, you no longer need absolutely every single human being spending their entire waking life actively searching for food.

29:49.380 --> 29:51.540
You can build permanent, fortified settlements.

29:51.940 --> 29:57.100
And crucially, you can afford to have people who specialize entirely in other non-food-producing tasks.

29:57.580 --> 29:59.680
You get the emergence of specialized intellectual labor.

30:00.020 --> 30:04.480
You get individuals who just spend their nights studying the movement of the stars.

30:05.020 --> 30:07.840
Which eventually gives birth to advanced mathematics and astronomy.

30:07.840 --> 30:15.840
You get specialized administrators who invent written language specifically to track and distribute the surplus grain in the city storehouses.

30:16.880 --> 30:18.980
Writing itself is born from surplus.

30:19.220 --> 30:30.740
You literally could not have modern science, modern medicine, or the deep dives we're doing right now without the massive caloric and cognitive surplus generated by that initial agricultural transition.

30:31.060 --> 30:37.000
And we see this exact same dynamical pattern repeat itself centuries later during the Industrial Revolution.

30:37.000 --> 30:38.780
Another massive bifurcation.

30:38.780 --> 30:49.840
If you read the historical accounts and literature from the late 18th and early 19th centuries, the early phases of industrialization were characterized by horrific, massive social disintegration.

30:49.920 --> 30:53.960
Millions of people were uprooted from their traditional ancestral farming communities.

30:54.160 --> 30:59.320
Crammed into incredibly polluted, disease-ridden slums and rapidly expanding cities.

30:59.320 --> 31:03.480
And subjected to brutal, unregulated labor conditions in factories.

31:03.480 --> 31:14.860
To the artists, philosophers, and average citizens observing society at that time, it genuinely looked like the moral, spiritual, and structural collapse of humanity.

31:15.000 --> 31:17.260
It looked exactly like a full catastrophe to them.

31:17.300 --> 31:23.340
You had movements like the Luddites literally smashing the weaving machinery because it was destroying their established way of life.

31:23.600 --> 31:24.680
They thought the world was ending.

31:24.680 --> 31:28.940
But stepping back and looking at the mathematical arc, it was not a catastrophe.

31:29.140 --> 31:30.980
It was another pitchfork bifurcation.

31:31.180 --> 31:32.680
It was a massive phase transition.

31:33.540 --> 31:34.820
The old mechanisms failed.

31:35.000 --> 31:44.020
The old, localized agricultural institutions simply could not handle the new realities of industrial production, mass urbanization, and rapid transportation.

31:44.760 --> 31:48.960
There was immense, undeniable suffering during the Mu sub-seat turbulence.

31:49.160 --> 31:53.640
But eventually, the complex system converged on a new set of societal attractors.

31:53.640 --> 32:03.540
That immense turbulence eventually necessitated and birthed the modern public education system, the implementation of comprehensive labor laws, the invention of the two-day weekend.

32:03.780 --> 32:08.600
Modern urban sanitation systems, and the foundations of advanced biomedical science.

32:08.860 --> 32:15.480
The coordination engine successfully upgraded its own internal error correction mechanisms to handle the new level of complexity.

32:15.480 --> 32:28.460
And for you listening to this, sitting in traffic or walking your dog, this is the ultimate empowering reframe when you feel completely overwhelmed by the sheer dizzying speed of the digital revolution today.

32:28.620 --> 32:31.220
The disruptive potential of artificial intelligence.

32:31.220 --> 32:37.380
Social media algorithms, fracturing our shared reality, the shifting and grinding of the geopolitical world order.

32:38.000 --> 32:47.560
You have to realize that the human beings who lived through the agricultural and industrial transitions felt the exact same crushing existential dread that you feel right now.

32:47.720 --> 32:49.140
You are not uniquely doomed.

32:49.560 --> 32:53.380
This anxiety is a feature, not a bug, of upgrading the coordination engine.

32:53.380 --> 33:01.100
We just happen to be the specific generation that is tasked with living inside the turbulent mo-sub neighborhood of this particular digital phase transition.

33:01.240 --> 33:05.860
Which is admittedly an inherently disorienting and uncomfortable place for a human being to be.

33:06.340 --> 33:14.540
And the paper suggests that one of the most acute, deeply felt symptoms of this societal disorientation is the modern epidemic of profound alienation.

33:14.540 --> 33:19.560
Yes. This is a theme that comes up in almost every cultural conversation I have.

33:20.160 --> 33:23.400
We live in these massive, densely populated metropolitan centers.

33:23.780 --> 33:27.720
We are physically surrounded by millions of other human beings every single day.

33:28.020 --> 33:33.100
Yet, report after report shows we feel incredibly, desperately lonely.

33:33.360 --> 33:35.160
It is a paradox of scale.

33:35.320 --> 33:40.620
We are hyper-connected digitally through our devices, yet we feel totally socially isolated.

33:40.620 --> 33:52.520
The dominant cultural narrative is that modern civilization, particularly the Internet, is actively destroying our innate human ability to connect, and that our social circles are rapidly contracting.

33:53.220 --> 33:57.040
But the paper argues that mathematically the exact opposite is happening.

33:57.260 --> 34:00.200
It does. It directly challenges the narrative of social contraction.

34:01.000 --> 34:06.460
The author introduces a brilliant, highly formalized mathematical concept in Appendix J called geozotic distance.

34:06.580 --> 34:07.520
Geozotic distance.

34:07.520 --> 34:13.220
I had never heard this specific term before reading this paper, but the moment I grasped it, so much of modern life made sense.

34:13.620 --> 34:16.380
Break down the actual formula for us, without getting lost in the weeds.

34:16.780 --> 34:24.680
Geozotic distance is a metric formulation designed to measure the true functional distance between two individual agents within a complex coordination system.

34:25.320 --> 34:28.500
It argues that distance is not just physical geography.

34:28.860 --> 34:29.840
So it's multidimensional.

34:29.840 --> 34:30.280
Yes.

34:30.900 --> 34:33.820
The author's formula combines four heavily weighted dimensions.

34:34.420 --> 34:39.880
Geographic distance, cultural distance, linguistic distance, and ideological distance.

34:40.440 --> 34:50.100
It uses what is called a Minkowski-like metric to synthesize these disparate dimensions into a single comprehensive measure of separation between two people.

34:50.100 --> 34:59.780
Now, a Minkowski-like metric sounds intimidating to the layman, but it's essentially just a way of calculating distance that factors in multiple variables at once, right?

34:59.800 --> 35:00.280
Yeah, exactly.

35:00.440 --> 35:03.280
Think of it like trying to calculate the true distance between two cities.

35:03.400 --> 35:05.140
You don't just draw a straight line on a map.

35:05.340 --> 35:09.980
You have to factor in the cost of the flight, the time it takes, the layovers, the difficulty of the terrain.

35:10.160 --> 35:11.740
It's a multidimensional measurement.

35:11.740 --> 35:13.860
That is an excellent way to visualize it.

35:14.360 --> 35:26.180
So if we look at human history, for roughly 99% of our species' existence, your geozotic distance mapped almost perfectly one-to-one onto your physical geographic distance.

35:26.340 --> 35:27.320
Because you couldn't travel.

35:27.460 --> 35:29.940
Because travel and communication were severely limited.

35:30.540 --> 35:41.160
If you were physically close to your tribe, you overwhelmingly shared the exact same culture, the exact same language, and the exact same religious and ideological worldview.

35:41.160 --> 35:48.960
And conversely, if someone lived just 100 miles away on the other side of a mountain range, they were geozotically incredibly far from you.

35:49.080 --> 35:53.440
They spoke a different language, worshipped different gods, and had a completely alien culture.

35:53.680 --> 36:07.620
And because of that historical reality, our effective radius of moral concern, meaning the circle of people who you genuinely cared about, who you felt a deep cooperative duty toward, and who you wouldn't steal from or harm, was extremely tight.

36:07.620 --> 36:12.380
It only practically applied to your immediate kin, your local village, or your specific tribe.

36:12.700 --> 36:25.420
But what the paper demonstrates mathematically, particularly in the graphs shown in Figure 4, is that with every major historical phase transition, this effective radius of moral concern has expanded discontinuously.

36:25.420 --> 36:30.640
And this is where the digital networks we've built completely break our ancient biological intuition.

36:31.440 --> 36:39.860
Today, thanks to the architecture of the internet and global mobility, I might have a physical neighbor who lives 20 feet away from me in my apartment building.

36:39.980 --> 36:42.180
Your geographic distance is practically zero.

36:42.460 --> 36:49.600
But perhaps we have vastly different political ideologies, completely different cultural backgrounds, and fundamentally opposing worldviews.

36:49.940 --> 36:54.560
According to the formula, geozotically, my neighbor and I are actually quite far apart.

36:54.560 --> 37:01.200
But at the exact same time, I can log on to a specialized forum, or a multiplayer video game, or a collaborative research network.

37:01.300 --> 37:09.020
And instantly connect with someone sitting in Tokyo, or Johannesburg, or London, who shares your exact, hyper-specific niche interests.

37:09.260 --> 37:13.060
My exact professional ambitions, and my exact ideological worldview.

37:13.740 --> 37:15.600
Geographically, they are thousands of miles away.

37:15.740 --> 37:18.140
But geographically, they are my next-door neighbor.

37:18.680 --> 37:19.440
They are my tribe.

37:19.440 --> 37:24.420
This metric fundamentally reframes the modern feeling of alienation you mentioned earlier.

37:24.980 --> 37:34.000
What the math suggests is that we are not actually experiencing a loss of human connection, nor are we experiencing a contraction of our social and empathetic capacities.

37:34.540 --> 37:36.620
The friction comes from institutional lag.

37:36.800 --> 37:37.200
Exactly.

37:37.540 --> 37:43.060
Our legacy institutions, which are still overwhelmingly built around the assumption of geographic proximity,

37:43.060 --> 37:56.060
think about local voting districts, regional tax bases, or community boards, are simply lagging decades behind our newly expanded, technologically-enabled capacity to connect deeply across vast geozotic distances.

37:56.360 --> 38:01.780
We feel alienated locally because our true geozotic peers are distributed globally.

38:01.980 --> 38:05.940
And it is not just about finding friends online who like the same obscure movies as you.

38:05.940 --> 38:10.440
This expansion fundamentally changes our entire moral framework as a species.

38:10.960 --> 38:12.840
Think about the concepts we take for granted today.

38:13.300 --> 38:16.520
We have the concept of universal, global human rights.

38:16.800 --> 38:24.140
We have robust environmental ethics where millions of people genuinely worry about the deforestation of a rainforest in a country they will absolutely never visit.

38:24.140 --> 38:26.500
We have global animal welfare movements.

38:27.000 --> 38:36.360
Our functional radius of moral concern has expanded from our immediate blood relatives to include people, species, and entire ecosystems on the opposite side of the planet.

38:36.560 --> 38:39.200
We haven't lost our humanity to the digital machine.

38:39.380 --> 38:41.760
Our humanity has miraculously scaled up.

38:42.340 --> 38:48.120
We are just feeling the intense psychological growing pains of developing a planetary-sized empathy.

38:48.120 --> 38:55.020
However, that massive expansion of scale and empathy brings us to a major, highly visible friction point in our daily lives.

38:55.760 --> 38:58.980
The paper addresses this directly, and I think it's crucial we cover it.

38:59.060 --> 38:59.940
The toxic debates.

39:00.120 --> 39:08.160
If civilization is indeed this robust, historically proven coordination engine, and if our moral radius is genuinely expanding,

39:08.700 --> 39:15.600
why are our actual day-to-day debates about the fate of civilization so incredibly toxic, exhausting, and paralyzing?

39:15.600 --> 39:21.520
Why does it feel fundamentally impossible to argue with people anymore without it devolving into a screaming match?

39:21.620 --> 39:23.540
Oh, this is so relevant. We have all been there.

39:23.800 --> 39:28.820
You get into a debate, maybe it's online in a comments section, or maybe it's at a family dinner like Thanksgiving.

39:29.200 --> 39:32.460
You're talking to your uncle, and he just starts hurling facts at you.

39:33.040 --> 39:34.720
It's not just one point.

39:34.720 --> 39:41.820
It's 50 different seemingly disconnected data points about hyperinflation, obscure supply chain failures,

39:42.240 --> 39:47.080
political corruption scandals you've never heard of, and localized ecological disasters.

39:47.300 --> 39:48.660
And you sit there paralyzed.

39:49.060 --> 39:54.360
Unable to even respond, because there is just too much information being thrown at you simultaneously

39:54.360 --> 39:56.980
to possibly fact-check in real time.

39:57.340 --> 40:00.140
The paper actually identifies this specific tactic, right?

40:00.260 --> 40:01.160
Yes, it does.

40:01.380 --> 40:03.820
In rhetorical theory, this is known as the GISH Gallop.

40:03.820 --> 40:08.680
It is a debate tactic where an opponent deliberately overwhelms you with a rabid-fire,

40:08.840 --> 40:14.180
voluminous series of arguments and data points, regardless of their individual accuracy or relevance.

40:14.300 --> 40:15.900
The sheer volume is the weapon.

40:16.420 --> 40:21.840
The sheer volume makes it cognitively and practically impossible for you to address and refute them all in real time,

40:22.240 --> 40:25.460
making it appear to an observer as though your opponent has won by default.

40:25.800 --> 40:30.620
